{
  "format": "wspradar.config",
  "schema_version": 1,
  "profile": {
    "id": "vanhamel_rx_buddy",
    "title": {
      "en": "Dr. Vanhamel et al. RX Antenna Rotation: Reproducing Figure 6’s 3 dB ΔSNR Step"
    },
    "description": {
      "en": "[Publication: Vanhamel, J., Machiels, W., & Lamy, H. (2022). Using the WSPR Mode for Antenna Performance Evaluation and Propagation Assessment on the 160-m Band](https://doi.org/10.1155/2022/4809313)\n\nApplies the paper’s 1.2 dB receiver-chain correction with Reference SNR Correction and compares the same transmitter decoded by ON4AWM0 and ON4AWM1 in the same WSPR cycle. In Segment Insight, check RX Compare Temporal → Δ SNR over Time: the pooled Full Range | All Directions view shows the broader upward transition, although it is not station-balanced. For the direct Figure 6 comparison, use Selected Station Evidence: M7AEO (IO82) → Δ SNR over Time (12h bins). Across 1,441 joint spots, median ΔSNR (ON4AWM0 ITA LWA II − corrected ON4AWM1 adapted shorted dipole) changes from −0.2 dB before 8 May to +2.8 dB afterward, reproducing the paper’s ≈3 dB step following the 90° antenna rotation.\n\nThis profile’s active result is RX Compare only. A separate no-benchmark Success run with the same Target and time window can provide supporting propagation context. In a historical separate Success analysis, M7AEO’s Station Success Rate + Evidence over Time (3h) and Target SNR showed night-classified opportunities at a 98% conditional Success Rate and −10 dB median successful Target SNR at 1 W, versus 44% and −20 dB in daylight—consistent with Figure 6’s pronounced day/night variation."
    }
  },
